  footnotes: []
english:
  title: A Eulogy for Minister Choe
  author: Lee In-ro
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Deep as a still pond, vast as the sea—
    its depths unknowable, such was your vessel of character,
    so profound that even the spirits could not glimpse within.

    Five colors blazed forth in splendor,
    shining together with sun and moon—
    such was your radiance,
    which ten centuries have not dimmed.

    You held all ages in your grasp,
    seeing emperors and sage-kings as mere courtyards—
    such was your wisdom,
    which all future generations shall take as mirror and example.

    Your path of learning knew no teacher but Confucius and the Duke of Zhou;
    your vow of purpose knew no measure but Gao Yao and Kui.

    Your noble retreat from office into quiet dwelling
    surpasses the gardens of Pingquan
    and the wine and poetry of the Green Fields.

    Beyond eighty winters, with rosy cheeks and silvered beard,
    leaning on your staff to wander mountains,
    lighting candles for chess—
    all who saw you said you were like the Yellow Stone Master
    walking in Xiapi.

    I, a latecomer to your acquaintance,
    found myself a Zhong Ziqi to your Elegy of Emei,
    a rough stone polished by your hand.
    You deemed my humble words worthy
    of dancing in the halls of ancient masters,
    fish from the bitter sea drawn up without remainder,
    my scattered verses gathered as precious medicine,
    shaped as song for the ear—

    Without your appreciation, who would have preserved them
    in silk and string, etched upon gold and stone,
    shining like the Northern Stars in eternal splendor?

    Now you have departed. Who remains to know me?

    Alas, your works endure like Mount Tai and the Yellow River,
    immovable upon this earth.
    Your words shine like gold and jade and white jade,
    growing ever more luminous with age.
    Your legacy is not bound by death or life—
    it neither waxes nor wanes.
    Why then should I grieve?

    Yet my voice rises in lamentation and tears,
    for this sorrow springs from my own heart.
    I offer this single cup and offer these humble words,
    a small vessel for a vast grief.
    Accept this offering.
  footnotes:
    - The Yellow Stone Master (黃石公) was a legendary hermit who taught the future Han general Zhang Liang, symbolizing the transmission of wisdom to worthy students
    - Zhong Ziqi (鍾子期) represents the ideal listener who truly understands music and poetry; here Lee uses it to mean Minister Choe understood and appreciated his writing
    - The 'five colors' reference relates to the five primary colors in Chinese aesthetics and symbolizes brilliance and virtue
